text: ANTIMICROBIAL AGENTS AND CHEMOTHERAPY, May 1992, p. 913-919 0066-4804/92/050913-07$02.00/0 Copyright ©) 1992, American Society for Microbiology Recent studies indicate that tetracycline antibiotics are divisible into two classes on the basis of their modes of action (14). Tetracycline, chlortetracycline, and minocycline (Fig. 1) as well as doxycycline (typical tetracyclines) prevent bacterial growth by inhibiting protein synthesis, whereas a second group (atypical tetracyclines) does not directly in- hibit bacterial protein synthesis at the level of the ribosome (14). The atypical analogs include chelocardin, anhydrotet- racycline, 6-thiatetracycline, anhydrochlortetracycline, and 4-epi-anhydrochlortetracycline (Fig. 1). Typical tetracyclines prevent protein synthesis by binding to a single site in the 30S ribosomal subunit, which prevents attachment of aminoacyl tRNA to the ribosomal acceptor (A) site (3, 14). The molecular basis by which atypical tetracyclines prevent bacterial growth is unknown. How- ever, because these agents rapidly inhibit incorporation of precursors into several macromolecules, it has been sug- gested that they perturb the organization of the bacterial cytoplasmic membrane (14). This report presents the results of experiments which have been conducted to explore further the mechanism of action of the atypical tetracyclines. We conclude that atypical tetracyclines interfere with membrane permeability, which in turn leads to cell lysis and death. In contrast, typical tetracyclines do not exhibit these effects. biology Section, University of L'Aquila, L'Aquila, Italy. MATERIALS AND METHODS Chemicals. The analogs tested, chelocardin, anhydrotetracycline, 6-thiatetracycline, anhydrochlortetracy- cline, and 4-epi-anhydrochlortetracycline, were bactericidal and caused the lysis of Escherichia coli accompa- nied by the release of the cytoplasmic enzyme 1-galactosidase into the supernatant. Examination by electron microscopy demonstrated that cells exposed to these analogs underwent marked morphological alterations that included the formation of numerous ghosts and the appearance of cellular debris in the culture medium. Although atypical tetracyclines promoted lysis in intact organisms, they did not cause lysis of E. coli spheroplasts, indicating that the analogs do not directly destroy the cytoplasmic membrane. These agents may promote cell lysis and death by interfering with the membrane's electrochemical gradient, which in turn leads to stimulation of autolytic enzyme activity and cellular lysis. The results support recently published data which indicate that tetracyclines are divisible into two classes on the basis of their modes of action. ratories. All other chemicals were purchased from standard commercial sources.

Addition of tetracyclines to cultures. Tetracyclines (10 mg/ml) were dissolved in dimethyl sulfoxide (20% [vol/vol]) immediately before use in experiments. Control experiments established that the quantity of dimethyl sulfoxide added to cultures has no effect on cell survival, cell growth, or cell morphology, as observed by electron microscopy. Bacteria and growth media. Escherichia coli K-12 3300 (lacI lacO lacY) was used throughout this study. This 3-galactosidase (EC 3.2.1.23) consti- organism synthesizes tutively (4). This strain was cultured in M63 minimal medium that was prepared as described previously (4). When solid medium was required, agar (1.5% [wt/vol]) was added to the same medium. Determination of viable cell number. Viable cell numbers were determined by diluting samples in sterile growth me- dium and plating the solution onto drug-free agar to deter- mine the number of viable bacteria (2, 5). Viable cell numbers were determined from replicate samples. MIC determinations. MICs were determined by an agar dilution method (14). A logarithmic-phase culture (10 ,ul) containing 1 x 106 to 5 x 106 CFU/ml was inoculated onto agar plates containing a range of antibiotic concentrations. Plates were incubated for 18 h at 37°C. The MIC was defined as the lowest concentration of antibiotic that inhibited growth of E. coli K-12 3300. Distinction between bacteriostatic and bactericidal antibiot- ics by turbidimetric measurements of bacterial growth. The distinction between bacteriostatic and bactericidal antibiot- ics was determined by turbidimetrically measuring bacterial growth essentially as described by Douglas and Freer (6). The procedure involved the addition of tetracyclines (15 ,ug/ml) to exponentially growing cultures of E. coli K-12 3300. After 30 min, cells were washed and resuspended in fresh growth medium at 37°C. The ability of the bacteria to resume growth was then monitored by determining the culture A550.

This was performed by remov- ing samples (1 ml) from the cultures, centrifugation (micro- centrifuge, 11,600 x g, 3 min), and estimation of ,B-galactosi- dase (4) in the cell-free supernatants. microscopic Early-logarithmic- phase cultures of E. coli K-12 3300 in minimal medium were incubated for 2 h with 15 gLg of chlortetracycline, anhydrotet- racycline, anhydrochlortetracycline, or chelocardin per ml. At 10- or 20-min intervals, samples of each culture and a corresponding control were collected on Nuclepore mem- branes (pore size, 0.2 to 0.5 ,um) by filtration for scanning electron microscopy. The filters were fixed in phosphate- buffered 2.5% glutaraldehyde, postfixed in osmium tetrox- ide, dehydrated in a graded series of ethanol, dried to the critical point from absolute ethanol, and sputter-coated with gold. They were examined either with a JEOL 6400F field emission scanning electron microscope or with a JEOL 100CX-II emission scanning electron microscope in the scanning mode. Additional samples from each time period were fixed similarly, pelleted by centrifugation, processed, embedded in epoxy resin, and stained with uranyl acetate and lead citrate for transmission electron microscopic exam- ination with a JEOL 100CX-II transmission electron micro- scope.

Chelocardin and anhydrochlortetracycline also caused the release of ,B-galactosidase, but there was a delay before the enzyme appeared in the culture supernatant (Fig. 4A and B, respectively). Morphological effects of tetracyclines. Bacteria were exam- ined by both transmission (Fig. 5) and scanning (Fig. 6) electron microscopy. The ultrastructural morphology of E. coli incubated with a typical, bacteriostatic tetracycline (chlortetracycline) for up to 2 h was indistinguishable from that of the corresponding drug-free control, with the one exception that the incidence of long filaments and branched cells was greater after 1 h of incubation with chlortetra- cycline and increased over time to an incidence of >5% of the population by 2 h. In addition, both the length of the filaments and the number of branches per cell increased with longer incubation times (data not shown). Filamen- tous and branched forms were also induced by anhydrochlo- rtetracycline (Fig. 5A) and by chelocardin and anhydrotet- racycline (data not shown). However, viewed by either scanning or transmission electron microscopy, it was evi- dent that these atypical, bactericidal tetracyclines also caused marked degenerative changes, lysis of cells, produc- tion of numerous vacant ghosts, and release of abundant cellular debris. with chelocardin, for which the delay in the appearance of the enzyme was approximately 30 min (Fig. 4A).

Atypical tetracyclines do not cause lysis of E. col sphero- plasts. Bacterial lysis and death mediated by the atypical tetracyclines might be the consequence of gross damage to the cytoplasmic membrane. To investigate this possibility, the effect of tetracyclines on the stability of E. coli sphero- plasts was examined. Addition of either typical or atypical tetracyclines (15 pug/ml) to spheroplasts in 20% (wt/vol) sucrose failed to lyse them during 60 min of incubation at 37°C (data not shown). However, addition of polymyxin B (15 pug/ml) or sodium dodecyl sulfate (15 jg/ml) led to the immediate lysis of spheroplasts (data not shown). DISCUSSION The results presented here confirm previous reports that 6-thiatetracycline and chelocardin are bactericidal agents (1, 13, 15). However, conclusions regarding the modes of action of these compounds have, until recently, been influenced by reports that both antibiotics inhibit bacterial protein synthe- sis at the level of the ribosome (3, 11, 15). Chopra (3) concluded that the bactericidal activity of 6-thi- atetracycline reflects a mode of ribosomal binding that differs from those of tetracyclines with bacteriostatic prop- erties. Recently, it has been established that the antibacterial activities of several tetracyclines, including chelocardin and 6-thiatetracycline, are not due to direct inhibition of protein synthesis at the level of the ribosome (14). In contrast, other MECHANISMS OF TETRACYCLINE ACTION f r o m h t t p : / / a a c . a s m . o r g / o n M a y b y T h e U n v e r s i t y

tetracyclines, e.g., chlortetracycline, minocycline, and tet- racycline, prevent bacterial growth by directly inhibiting protein synthesis at the ribosome (14). The data presented here support the division of tetracyclines into two classes on the basis of their modes of action (14). Atypical tetracy- clines, which are unable to inhibit protein synthesis directly, were bactericidal and promoted cell lysis; typical tetracy- clines, which directly inhibit protein synthesis, were bacte- riostatic and had no tendency to cause lysis. Assuming that release of j-galactosidase reflects bacterial lysis, killing of organisms by atypical tetracyclines occurs concomitantly with lysis. Thus, substantial amounts of n-ga- lactosidase were released during the period required to kill the majority of E. coli cells. Although all atypical tetracy- clines caused cell lysis and death, the onset of these events was delayed in chelocardin-treated cultures. An explanation for this is not available. The asterisks indicate cellular debris arising from lysis of cells (magnification, x 15,000). Lysis of bacteria results from one of the following mech- anisms: (i) direct solubilization of the cytoplasmic membrane (7, 10, 16), (ii) membrane deenergization (8, 9, 12, 17), or (iii) specific inhibition of certain membrane-located, penicillin- binding proteins (10, 16). Lysis by mechanisms (i) and (ii) results from the triggering of autolytic enzymes, which cause peptidoglycan degradation and lysis of cells that are not osmotically protected (10, 16). Lysis by mechanism (i) does not, however, result from cell wall degradation (10). Rapid lysis of bacterial spheroplasts by an antimicrobial agent provides good evidence that it solubilizes the cytoplas- mic membrane (7, 16). Since atypical tetracyclines failed to lyse spheroplasts, it is unlikely that they mediate lysis by

To exert their effects, atypical tetracyclines presumably interact with the cytoplasmic membrane. This probably relates to the increased lipophilicity of the atypical tetracy- clines. These derivatives all have a relatively planar aro- matic BCD ring system (i.e., the rings containing carbons 5 through 7; Fig. 1) which likely promotes a strong association with the lipid bilayer of the cytoplasmic membrane. In addition, the conformational equilibrium between hydropho- bic and hydrophilic forms that appears to exist with the classical tetracyclines containing a 3-hydroxyl group at C-6 is probably shifted more toward a hydrophobic form in the atypical series because of the planarity of the BCD rings (14). This shift in equilibrium would be enhanced by the largely nonpolar environment of the membrane. The typical tetracyclines, in contrast, are able to pass through the membrane without altering any biochemical functions and bind to the ribosomal target in the cytoplasm (14). The morphological alterations observed in cultures exposed to atypical tetracyclines presumably reflect the biochemical phenomena that occur within the cell envelope following interaction of the agents with the cytoplasmic membrane. In all cases (and at all time periods), cultures exposed to anhydrotetracyclines contained cells that exhibited normal morphology and others that were abnormal. The former may mechanism (i). Since there is no evidence that tetracyclines interact specifically with penicillin-binding proteins, mecha- nism (iii) is unlikely to be responsible for tetracycline- induced lysis. Therefore, atypical tetracyclines may mediate lysis by mechanism (ii), i.e., membrane deenergization fol- lowed by cellular autolysis. ANTIMICROB. AGENTs CHEMOTHER.
